rdshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Terry","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: from the Norman personal name <i>T(h)erry</i> (Old French <i>Thierri</i>), a short form of <i>Theodoric</i>, which is composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>theud</i> ‘people, race’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful), rich’. <i>Theodoric</i> was the name of the Ostrogothic leader (<i>c.</i> 454–526) who invaded Italy in 488 and established his capital at Ravenna in 493. His name was sometimes taken as a derivative of Greek <i>Theodōros</i> (see   Theodore  ). An Anglo-Norman family of this name has been in County Cork, Ireland, since the 13th century.","Irish: sometimes an Anglicized (‘translated’) form of Gaelic <b>Mac Toirdhealbhaigh</b> (see   Turley  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Terris","meanings":["Scottish (Fife): habitational name from Tarras in Rafford (Morayshire).","Catalan and southern French (Pyrénées-Orientales): from a personal name derived from the ancient Germanic name <i>Theodoric</i> (see   Terry  ).","French (southern); Catalan (<b>Terrís</b>): topographic name derived from French <i>terre</i>, Catalan <i>terra</i> ‘ground, earth, land’."]},{"name":"Tarry","meanings":["English (Northamptonshire and Leicestershire; of Norman origin): variant of   Terry   1."]},{"name":"Tyrie","meanings":["Scottish (Angus and Glasgow): habitational name from Tyrie (Perthshire) or Tyrie (Aberdeenshire). The placenames are from Gaelic <i>tìr</i> ‘(arable) land’ + a placename forming suffix (perhaps) <i>–in</i>.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Terry  ."]},{"name":"Theodore","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Serge, Henri, Pierre, Alide, Andre, Antoine, Benoit, Berthony, Chantal, Daphnee, Edouard, Guilene.","French and Mauritian (<b>Théodore</b>); West Indian (in Haiti, Martinique, and Guadeloupe <b>Théodore</b>); English and Welsh: from a personal name derived from Greek <i>Theodōros</i>, a compound of <i>theos</i> ‘God’ + <i>dōron</i> ‘gift’, which was relatively popular in the Middle Ages because of its auspicious meaning. The name was borne by several early Christian saints. There was considerable confusion with the ancient Germanic name <i>Theodoric</i> (see   Terry  ). In Wales, the personal name <i>Theodore</i> was also adopted as an approximation to the Welsh name <i>Tewdwr</i> (see   Tudor  ). In North America, this surname has absorbed various other European cognates and their derivatives, e.g. Greek   Theodorakis  , Macedonian <b>Todorovski</b>, and Serbian <b>Todorović</b> (see   Todorovic  )."]},{"name":"Thierry","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Leonce, Olivier, Alain, Armand, Fernand.","French: from the Old French personal name <i>Thierri</i>, a short form of ancient Germanic <i>Theodoric</i> (see   Terry  ), composed of the elements <i>theud</i> ‘people, race’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful), rich’. This surname is also found in Germany.","History: Francis-Jean Thierry from France married Frances Bowen Blake in Marietta, OH, in 1815. Joseph Thierry from Germany married Susanna Plabuet probably in Detroit, MI, in 1846. Louis Thierry from Mulhouse in Haut-Rhin married Amelia Appelt probably in Michigan <i>c.</i> 1863."]},{"name":"Thilges","meanings":["German: patronymic from <i>Tilge</i>, a pet form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Theodoric</i> (see   Terry  )."]},{"name":"Tear","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>ter(e)</i> ‘of fine appearance or character’. The name may sometimes have been confused with   Terry  .","Possibly an altered form of German   Thier  .","Manx: variant of   Teare  ."]},{"name":"Tjarks","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Fritz, Hermann.","East Frisian and North German: patronymic from <i>Tjark</i>, a short form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Theodoric</i> (see   Terry  ), composed of the elements <i>theud</i> ‘people, race’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful), rich’."]}]},{"name":"Mrs.","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Latin <i>Ursus</i> ‘bear’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":20,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":45,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":58,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Terry was born about 1270, in England. She had at least 1 daughter with Edward Terry."},"et":{"abt 1270–":"umbes 1270–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1297–1370":"1297–1370","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1315":"1315","abt 1270":"umbes 1270","1297":"1297","1370":"1370","1270":"1270","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"abt 1270–":"noin 1270–Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1297–1370":"1297–1370","1270–Female":"1270–Kuollut","1315":"1315","abt 1270":"noin 1270","1297":"1297","1370":"1370","1270":"1270","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oxford, Oxfords